Diagnosis: Hypopygus lepturus
is diagnosed from congeners by the following combination of characters: the absence of the sixth infraorbital bone (versus presence in all congeners except
H. hoedemani
and
H. minissimus
), the total number of anal-fin rays (109–135 versus 136–170 in all congeners except
H. hoedemani
and
H. minissimus
), the length of the caudal filament (48.4–80.9% of LEA versus 31.1–48.1 in
H. hoedemani
), the presence of scales at midbody (versus absence in
H. minissimus
), the presence of oblique bands (versus absence in
H. minissimus
), and the dorsal rami of the intermittent branch of anterior lateral line nerve visible as two black parallel lines (versus not visible in
H. ortegai
).
